01:04:56.610 --> 01:04:58.470
And before I moved to exercise,

01:04:58.470 --> 01:05:00.310
I also just want to highlight something

01:05:00.310 --> 01:05:02.010
that comes up every few years

01:05:02.010 --> 01:05:06.320
and has largely been considered myth now,

01:05:06.320 --> 01:05:09.080
but that is actually more interesting

01:05:09.080 --> 01:05:10.840
than most people might think,

01:05:10.840 --> 01:05:13.610
which is this issue of spot reduction.

01:05:13.610 --> 01:05:16.370
You know, in the 80s and 90s,

01:05:16.370 --> 01:05:17.930
there were a lot of commercials,

01:05:17.930 --> 01:05:19.483
late night infomercials,

01:05:20.450 --> 01:05:22.660
where they would talk
about spot reduction.

01:05:22.660 --> 01:05:25.610
If you do sit ups, will
you lose abdominal fat?

01:05:25.610 --> 01:05:27.223
If you do hip raises or glute raises,

01:05:27.223 --> 01:05:29.600
will you lose gluten hip fat.

01:05:29.600 --> 01:05:33.380
And I think everybody
knows now believes that,

01:05:33.380 --> 01:05:36.390
and understands that fat metabolism

01:05:36.390 --> 01:05:38.880
is something that happens
systemically throughout the body.

01:05:38.880 --> 01:05:41.210
That some body fat is
quote unquote more stubborn

01:05:41.210 --> 01:05:42.043
than others.

01:05:42.043 --> 01:05:44.660
Everyone varies in where
they tend to store fat

01:05:44.660 --> 01:05:46.284
or lose fat last.

01:05:46.284 --> 01:05:48.460
Number of factors that influence that,

01:05:48.460 --> 01:05:51.370
and in particular hormone receptors.

01:05:51.370 --> 01:05:56.370
But now at least in the
scientific literature,

01:05:57.160 --> 01:06:00.450
spot reduction and the possibility of real

01:06:00.450 --> 01:06:04.200
true spot reduction reductions
in fat in a targeted way,

01:06:04.200 --> 01:06:06.930
a body part or body area targeted way

01:06:06.930 --> 01:06:11.760
is becoming more of a reality
and may be a reality soon,

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:16.760
because exercise that
triggers the activation

01:06:16.760 --> 01:06:18.340
of these nerve fibers,

01:06:18.340 --> 01:06:20.850
these neurons that innervate fat.

01:06:20.850 --> 01:06:25.240
In theory, if you can increase
the amount of epinephrin

01:06:25.240 --> 01:06:28.830
released at those particular
fat pads as they're called,

01:06:28.830 --> 01:06:30.410
they're actually called fat pads

01:06:30.410 --> 01:06:32.350
in the scientific literature.

01:06:32.350 --> 01:06:35.810
In theory, you could increase mobilization

01:06:35.810 --> 01:06:39.350
from those particular body fat sites.

01:06:39.350 --> 01:06:40.183
Okay?

01:06:40.183 --> 01:06:44.260
So because the new view that
the modern understanding

01:06:44.260 --> 01:06:46.980
is that it's not adrenaline
released systemically

01:06:46.980 --> 01:06:49.870
kind of bathing all your fat tissue,

01:06:49.870 --> 01:06:52.570
but rather its neurons
releasing adrenaline

01:06:52.570 --> 01:06:55.063
epinephrin locally that in theory,

01:06:56.010 --> 01:06:59.290
exercise that stimulates
the release of epinephrin

01:06:59.290 --> 01:07:02.950
or exercise coupled
with things like shiver

01:07:02.950 --> 01:07:04.750
or low grade shaking movement,

01:07:04.750 --> 01:07:08.890
or the NEAT, the non-exercise
activity thermogenesis

01:07:09.790 --> 01:07:14.200
could in theory lead to local enhancement

01:07:14.200 --> 01:07:16.650
of mobilization of fat tissue.

01:07:16.650 --> 01:07:18.030
So I think that spot reduction

01:07:18.030 --> 01:07:21.240
actually will soon be
something that's possible

01:07:21.240 --> 01:07:23.290
using the appropriate technology.

01:07:23.290 --> 01:07:24.860
What does this mean for you now?

01:07:24.860 --> 01:07:28.900
What could you possibly do
with this information now?

01:07:28.900 --> 01:07:33.240
Well, I think it speaks to the fact

01:07:33.240 --> 01:07:36.980
that if one is going to engage in exercise

01:07:36.980 --> 01:07:39.420
that doing exercises that involve

01:07:39.420 --> 01:07:43.000
lots of different body parts and movements

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:46.250
is likely to encourage the maintenance

01:07:46.250 --> 01:07:48.950
and or growth of these neurons

01:07:48.950 --> 01:07:51.020
that innervate fat throughout the body.

01:07:51.020 --> 01:07:53.920
What this means is changing
up the pattern of exercise,

01:07:53.920 --> 01:07:56.440
engaging in novel types of movements

01:07:56.440 --> 01:07:59.070
may actually be one
way that one can access

01:07:59.070 --> 01:08:02.010
these so-called stubborn body fat pads.

01:08:02.010 --> 01:08:03.440
Now, there's a little bit of speculation

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:04.970
in the statement that I'm making,

01:08:04.970 --> 01:08:06.480
but if you think about it it makes sense.

01:08:06.480 --> 01:08:09.050
If you become very adapted
to a particular pattern

01:08:09.050 --> 01:08:10.610
of exercise,

01:08:10.610 --> 01:08:12.700
whether or not you're subcaloric or not,

01:08:12.700 --> 01:08:15.390
you're on maintenance calories are not,

01:08:15.390 --> 01:08:18.600
you are oxidizing some fat always,

01:08:18.600 --> 01:08:22.370
and you're utilizing the
neurons that innervate fat

01:08:22.370 --> 01:08:23.300
in a regular way.

01:08:23.300 --> 01:08:27.600
And pretty soon this innervation
is going to shut off,

01:08:27.600 --> 01:08:31.660
because there's no reason why
this neural innervation of fat

01:08:31.660 --> 01:08:33.650
should continue to release epinephrin

01:08:33.650 --> 01:08:35.900
unless you give it a
strong stimulus like cold

01:08:35.900 --> 01:08:38.810
or the fidgeting or in this case

01:08:38.810 --> 01:08:41.240
to do novel forms of exercise.

01:08:41.240 --> 01:08:44.330
And there's some anecdotal evidence

01:08:44.330 --> 01:08:46.040
and I don't even want to call it data,

01:08:46.040 --> 01:08:48.670
but anecdotal evidence
that people who have,

01:08:48.670 --> 01:08:50.200
quote on quote stubborn body fat,

01:08:50.200 --> 01:08:52.810
if they start to adopt
new patterns of exercise,

01:08:52.810 --> 01:08:56.130
they can start to access
those stubborn fat pads.

01:08:56.130 --> 01:08:57.960
And again, fat pads is the correct way

01:08:57.960 --> 01:09:00.810
to refer to these in the
scientific literature.

01:09:00.810 --> 01:09:04.260
So what we're focusing
on today is the fact

01:09:04.260 --> 01:09:08.190
that fat indeed will be
mobilized and oxidized

01:09:08.190 --> 01:09:10.500
in response to a deficit in calories.

01:09:10.500 --> 01:09:13.697
But that the way that neurons
control those fat pads

01:09:13.697 --> 01:09:15.235
and those body fat stores,

01:09:15.235 --> 01:09:17.840
affords you a lot more control

01:09:17.840 --> 01:09:20.560
than perhaps you ever previously thought.

01:09:20.560 --> 01:09:22.720
So let's talk about movement.

01:09:22.720 --> 01:09:24.410
And the more traditional
kinds of movement,

01:09:24.410 --> 01:09:27.680
aka exercise has been
shown to lead to increases

01:09:27.680 --> 01:09:31.900
in metabolism and fat
loss to greater degrees

01:09:31.900 --> 01:09:33.300
depending on whether or not for,

01:09:33.300 --> 01:09:36.060
instance you're fasted
when you do it or not,

01:09:36.060 --> 01:09:37.730
whether or not you do your cardio first

01:09:37.730 --> 01:09:39.810
or your resistance training first.

01:09:39.810 --> 01:09:42.210
And this is again in the literature

01:09:42.210 --> 01:09:43.940
for which there's a lot of controversy,

01:09:43.940 --> 01:09:47.060
but in digging through
all the studies on this,

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:49.960
we're finally starting to
arrive at a consensus of,

01:09:49.960 --> 01:09:51.690
when is best to do exercise?

01:09:51.690 --> 01:09:55.960
And what types of exercise to
do if your goal is fat loss?

01:09:55.960 --> 01:09:59.500
The topic of exercise is a
kind of controversial one,

01:09:59.500 --> 01:10:01.490
not as controversial as nutrition and diet

01:10:01.490 --> 01:10:03.780
which we will talk about in a few minutes.

01:10:03.780 --> 01:10:06.880
But it's a particularly interesting one,

01:10:06.880 --> 01:10:09.840
because different types
of exercising gauge

01:10:09.840 --> 01:10:12.060
the musculature of the body
and the heart and the lungs

01:10:12.060 --> 01:10:13.570
in different ways,

01:10:13.570 --> 01:10:15.730
and can have vastly
different effects on things

01:10:15.730 --> 01:10:18.290
like hormones and metabolism
depending on whether

01:10:18.290 --> 01:10:19.890
or not it's of high intensity,

01:10:19.890 --> 01:10:22.340
moderate intensity or low intensity.

01:10:22.340 --> 01:10:24.610
So rather than think about weight training

01:10:24.610 --> 01:10:27.080
versus cardiovascular exercise,

01:10:27.080 --> 01:10:29.910
I think the most simple way,

01:10:29.910 --> 01:10:33.780
the most fluid way to have this
conversation about exercise

01:10:33.780 --> 01:10:38.150
and fat loss is in terms of
three general types of training.

01:10:38.150 --> 01:10:40.190
Whether or not it's done
with weights or body weight

01:10:40.190 --> 01:10:42.150
doesn't really matter.

01:10:42.150 --> 01:10:45.060
And those are high
intensity interval training.

01:10:45.060 --> 01:10:47.410
Something that's seems to have
gained a lot of popularity

01:10:47.410 --> 01:10:48.310
in recent years.

01:10:48.310 --> 01:10:49.860
So-called HITT, H-I-I-T.

01:10:49.860 --> 01:10:52.260
So high intensity interval training.

01:10:52.260 --> 01:10:54.040
Sprint interval training.

01:10:54.040 --> 01:10:57.050
So that's going to be very
high intensity or SIT,

01:10:57.050 --> 01:11:01.290
or moderate intensity
continuous training, M-I-C-T.

01:11:01.290 --> 01:11:05.830
So we've got HIIT, SIT and MICT, M-I-C-T.

01:11:05.830 --> 01:11:08.500
And we can get a little bit
more precise if you'd like.

01:11:08.500 --> 01:11:11.260
I'm not somebody who measures
my VO2 max or anything

01:11:11.260 --> 01:11:12.100
while I exercise.

01:11:12.100 --> 01:11:14.670
I generally know whether
or not I'm doing something

01:11:14.670 --> 01:11:16.300
I could continue for a very long time,

01:11:16.300 --> 01:11:17.920
or whether or not I'm doing something

01:11:17.920 --> 01:11:21.610
that I realize is going
to be of short duration

01:11:21.610 --> 01:11:22.443
high-intensity.

01:11:22.443 --> 01:11:27.443
But if you'd like to
map this to VO2 max SIT,

01:11:27.600 --> 01:11:30.040
this sprint interval training was defined

01:11:30.040 --> 01:11:33.440
as all out greater than 100% of VO2 max

01:11:33.440 --> 01:11:37.000
bursts of activity that
lasts eight to 30 seconds

01:11:37.000 --> 01:11:39.160
intersperse with less
intense recovery periods.

01:11:39.160 --> 01:11:41.540
So this would be sprinting downfield

01:11:41.540 --> 01:11:43.230
for eight to 30 seconds,

01:11:43.230 --> 01:11:46.500
then maybe walking back
for about a minute or two

01:11:46.500 --> 01:11:48.270
and then sprinting again
and then continuing.

01:11:48.270 --> 01:11:49.450
So that would be SIT.

01:11:49.450 --> 01:11:53.310
HIIT, H-I-I-T is defined as submaximal,

01:11:53.310 --> 01:11:57.060
so 80 to a hundred percent
of VO2 max bursts of activity

01:11:57.060 --> 01:12:00.320
that lasts 60 to 240 seconds

01:12:00.320 --> 01:12:02.880
intersperse with less
intense recovery periods.

01:12:02.880 --> 01:12:05.020
So on a standard 400 meter track,

01:12:05.020 --> 01:12:07.170
just to give this a
little bit of a visual,

01:12:08.540 --> 01:12:11.250
a four minute mile would be
fantastic for most people,

01:12:11.250 --> 01:12:13.250
although people run faster
than that of course.

01:12:13.250 --> 01:12:15.350
So that's four 60 seconds laps,

01:12:15.350 --> 01:12:17.520
but that's back to back to back.

